  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are specific laws targeting money laundering in many countries. In the United States, key anti-money laundering (AML) laws include:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates record-keeping and reporting requirements\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Criminalizes money laundering as a federal offense\n- Allows prosecution of individuals who knowingly engage in money laundering\n\n3. USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Enhanced AML regulations\n- Increased reporting and monitoring requirements\n- Strengthened cooperation between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\nOther countries have similar laws, such as:\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- United Kingdom's Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Canada's Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act\n\nThese laws typically:\n- Define money laundering as a criminal offense\n- Require financial institutions to implement compliance programs\n- Mandate reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Establish penalties for non-compliance\n- Facilitate international cooperation in tracking and preventing money laundering\n\nThese regulations aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
